 where you got it' b'from. if your server came from a different source as the rest of your x system,' b'give details of that, too. give the machine type, operating system, and o/s' b'version for both the client and server machine. it may also be appropriate to' b'mention the window manager, compiler, and display hardware type you are using.' b'' b'then tell exactly what you are doing, exactly what happens, and what' b'you expected/wanted to happen. if it is a command that fails, include the' b'exact transcript of your session in the message. if a program you wrote' b"doesn't work the way you expect, include as little of the source necessary" b'(just a small test case, please!) for readers to reproduce the problem.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the trade magazines (unix world, unix review, computer language, etc.)' b'are publishing more articles on x. two x-specific publications include:' b'' b'- o\'reilly and associates publishes "the x resource: a practical' b'journal of the x window system" morris st. #a, sebastapol, ca b'' b'- the x journal is started bi-monthly publication september on a' b'variety of x topics. subscription information: the x journal, subscriber' b'services, dept xxx, p.o. box denville, nj usa. editorial' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'xt: the x toolkit intrinsics is a library layered on xlib which' b'provides the functionality from which the widget sets are built. an "xt-based"' b'program is an application which uses one of those widget sets and which uses' b'intrinsics mechanisms to manipulate the widgets.' b'xmu: the xmu library is a collection of miscellaneous utility functions' b'useful in building various applications and widgets.' b'xaw: the athena widget set is the mit-implemented sample widget set' b'distributed with x11 source.' b'xm: the osf/motif widget set from the open software foundation; binary' b'kits are available from many hardware vendors.' b'xhp (xw): the hewlett-packard widget set was originally based on r2++,' b'but several sets of patches exist which bring it up to r3, as it is distributed' b'on the x11r4 tapes. supplemental patches are available to use it with r4/r5.' b'clx: the common lisp x interface is a common lisp equivalent to xlib.' b'xdmcp: the x display manager protocol provides a uniform mechanism for' b'a display such as an x terminal to request login service from a remote host.' b'xlfd: the x logical font description conventions describes a standard' b'logical font description and conventions to be used by clients so that they' b'can query and access those resources.' b'rtfm: common expert-speak meaning "please locate and consult the' b'relevant documentation read the forgotten manual".' b'utsl: a common expression meaning "take advantage of the fact that you' b'aren\'t limited by a binary license use the source, luke".' b'api: application-programmer interface. the function calls, etc., in' b'a programming library.' b'bdf: bitmap distribution format; a human-readable format for uncompiled' b'x fonts.' b'gui: graphical user interface.' b'uil: the user interface language, part of osf/motif which lets' b'programmers specify a widget hierarchy in a simple "outline" form' b'wcl: the widget creation language, a package which extends the' b'understanding of the xt resource format such that a widget hierarchy and' b'actions on the widgets can be specified through the resources file' b"gil: the file format put out by sun's openwindows developers guide b'uims: user interface management system' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the inter-client communication conventions manual is one of the' b'official x consortium standards documents that define the x environment. it' b'describes the conventions that clients must observe to coexist peacefully with' b'other clients sharing the same server. if you are writing x clients, you need' b'to read and understand the icccm, in particular the sections discussing the' b'selection mechanism and the interaction between your client and the window' b'manager. get it either:' b'- as part of the r4 distribution from mit' b'- in the later editions of the scheifler/gettys "x window system" book' b'- as an appendix in the new version of o\'reilly\'s volume "x protocol' b'reference manual." a version in old copies of their volume is obsolete.' b'the version in the digital press book is much more readable, thanks to' b"the efforts of digital press's editors to improve the english and the" b'presentation.' b'' b'[from david rosenthal, b'' b"- the icccm was updated for r5; updates are published in o'reilly's" b'"programmer\'s supplement for release the complete document is on the r5' b'tapes.' b'' b'alternate definition: the icccm is generally the m in "rtfm" and is' b'the most-important of the least-read x documents.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the mit x consortium was formed in january of to further the' b'development of the x window system and has as its major goal the promotion of' b'cooperation within the computer industry in the creation of standard software' b'interfaces at all layers in the x window system environment.' b"mit's role is to provide the vendor-neutral architectural and" b'administrative leadership required to make this work. membership in the' b'consortium open to any organization. there are two categories of membership,' b'member (for large organizations) and affiliate (for smaller organizations).' b"most of the consortium's activities take place via electronic mail," b'with meetings when required. as designs and specifications take shape,' b'interest groups are formed from experts in the participating organizations.' b'typically a small multi-organization architecture team leads the design, with' b'others acting as close observers and reviewers. once a complete specification' b'is produced, it may be submitted for formal technical review by the consortium' b'as a proposed standard. the standards process typically includes public' b'review (outside the consortium) and a demonstration of proof of concept.' b'your involvement in the public review process or as a member or' b'affiliate of the consortium is welcomed.' b'write to: bob scheifler, mit x consortium, laboratory for computer' b'science, technology square, cambridge, ma b'' b'[for complete information see the xconsortium man page from the x11r4' b'distribution, from which this information is adapted.] b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'open look and motif are two graphical user interfaces (guis). open look' b'was developed by sun with help from at&t and many industry reviewers; motif was' b'developed by the open software foundation (osf) with input from many osf' b'members.' b'' b'open look is primarily a user-interface specification and style-guide;' b'there are several toolkits which can be used to produce open look applications.' b'motif includes an api specification; the only sanctioned motif toolkit is the' b'one from osf. however, there are other toolkits which can be used to produce' b"programs which look and behave like osf/motif; one of these, parcplace's" b'(formerly solbourne\'s) oi, is a "virtual toolkit" which provides objects in the' b"style of open look and motif, at the user's choice." b'' b'open look gui is also the name of a product from at&t, comprising' b'their open look intrinsics toolkit and a variety of applications.' b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'open windows is a sun product that encompasses: a window system' b'that combines a news and x11-compliant server (x/news); a user-interface' b'specification (open look) and a series of toolkits that implement it (including' b'the sunview-like xview and the xt-based olit); xlib and xt implementations; and' b'a number of utilities (olwm window manager, filemgr, shelltool, etc.).' b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'decwindows is a dec product that encompasses: an x11 server; the xui' b'toolkit, including the dwt widget set and uil; xlib and xt implementations; a' b'session manager; and a number of utilities (dxwm window manager, dxcalendar,' b'dxpsview, etc.).' b'' b'(at some point motif flavors of the toolkit and applications will be shipped.)' b'[8/90]' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'pex is the "phigs extension to x".' b'phigs stands for "programmer\'s hierarchical interactive graphics' b'system" and is essentially a library of functions that simplifies the creation' b'and manipulation of 3d graphics. many platforms are capable of performing in' b'hardware the computations involved in rendering 3d objects; the extension' b'allows the client (phigs in this case) to take advantage of the specialized' b'hardware for 3d graphics.' b'sun microsystems is currently contracted to develop a freely' b'redistributable (copyright similar to the current x copyright) sample' b'implementation. source and documentation are available in the r5 release.' b'several vendors are currently selling independently-developed pex servers for' b'their workstations and x terminals.' b'' b'[last modified b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'there are several options for using x over serial lines:' b'' b'slip serial line ip; this is both a mechanism and a protocol for sending ip' b'packets over point-to-point serial links. it has been around for several years,' b'and implementations are available for many of the major tcp/ip implementations.' b'most x terminal vendors supply this as a checkoff item, although nobody really' b'ever uses it since it is horribly slow. the tcp/ip headers add bytes per' b'packet and the tcp/ip encoding of the x protocol is rather verbose (rightfully' b'so; it is optimized for packing and unpacking over high-speed links).' b'' b'cslip compressed header slip; this is a variant of slip that compresses the' b"40 bytes of tcp/ip headers down to about or bytes. it still doesn't do" b'anything about reencoding the x protocol. modems that do compression can help,' b'but they increase packet latency (it takes time to dribble the uncompressed' b'data through typical serial interfaces, plus the compression assembly time).' b'' b'ppp point-to-point protocol; this is an emerging standard for point-to-point' b'links over serial lines that has a more complete set of option negotiation than' b'slip. a growing number of people see the combination of ppp for the serial' b'line management and cslip for the header compression as becoming common for' b'running normal tcp/ip protocols over serial lines. running raw x over the wire' b'still needs compression somewhere to make it usable.' b'' b'xremote this is the name of both a protocol and set of products originally' b'developed by ncd for squeezing the x protocol over serial lines. in addition' b'to using a low level transport mechanism similar to ppp/cslip, xremote removes' b'redundancies in the x protocol by sending deltas against previous packets and' b'using lzw to compress the entire data stream. this work is done by either a' b'pseudo-x server or "proxy" running on the host or in a terminal server. there' b'are several advantages to doing compression outside the modem:' b"(1)\tyou don't *have* to have compressing modems in there if you wouldn't" b'otherwise be using them (e.g. if you were going to be directly' b'connected), and' b'(2)\tit reduces the i/o overhead by cutting down on the number of bytes that' b'have to cross the serial interface, and' b'(3)\tin addition to the effects of it reduces the latency in delivering' b'packets by not requiring the modem to buffer up the data waiting for' b'blocks to compress.' b'' b'lbx low bandwidth x; this is an x consortium project that is working on a' b'standard for this area. it is being chaired by ncd and xerox and is using' b"ncd's xremote protocol as a stepping stone in developing the new protocol. lbx" b'will go beyond xremote by adding proxy caching of commonly-used information' b'(e.g. connection setup data, large window properties, font metrics, keymaps,' b'etc.) and a more efficient encoding of the x protocol. the hope is to have a' b'standard ready for public review in the first half of next year and a sample' b'implementation available in r6.' b'' b'additional technical information about how xremote works and a few notes on how' b'lbx might be different are available via anonymous ftp from export.lcs.mit.edu' b'in contrib/ in the following files:' b'xremote-slides.ps slides describing xremote' b'xremote-lbx-diffs.ps more slides describing some of lbx' b'' b'' b"there is also a set of slides on export from jim fulton's talk at" b'the 7th mit x technical conference.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the window manager in x is just another client it is not part of the' b'x window system, although it enjoys special privileges and so there is' b'no single window manager; instead, there are many which support different ways' b'for the user to interact with windows and different styles of window layout,' b'decoration, and keyboard and colormap focus. in approximate chronological order' b'(generally, the more recent ones are more conformant with the icccm):' b'' b'wm: this simple title-bar window manager was phased out in r2 or r3' b'uwm: the universal window manager is still popular for its speed,' b'although it is very outdated. moved to contrib/ on the r4 tape.' b"twm (old): tom's window manager was among the first non-mit window" b'managers and offered the user a great deal of customization options in a' b're-parenting window manager.' b'awm: the ardent window manager remains a hotbed for hackers and offers' b'some features (dynamic menus) not found on more current window managers' b'cwm: cwm is part of the andrew system.' b"rtl: siemen's window manager tiles windows so that they don't overlap" b'and resizes the window with the focus to its preferred size.' b"dxwm: digital's dxwm is part of the decwindows offering" b"hpwm: hp's window manager offers a 3d look; it is a precursor of mwm" b'mwm: the motif window manager is part of the osf/motif toolkit' b"tekwm: tektronix's window manager offering" b'olwm (sun): olwm implements the open look gui and some of the style' b'guide functionality' b'olwm (at&t): ditto' b"gwm: bull's generic window manager emulates others with a built-in" b'lisp interpreter. version 1.7h is on the r5 contrib tape; 1.7n is on' b'avahi.inria.fr and export.lcs.mit.edu. b'm_swm: the sigma window manager is on the r4 tape' b"pswm: sun's postscript-based pswm is part of the openwindows release" b"swm: solbourne's swm is based on the oi toolkit and offers multiple" b'gui support and also a panned virtual window; configuration information comes' b'from the resources file' b"twm (new): mit's new tab window manager from the r4 tape is a reworked" b'twm and is the basis for several derivatives, including the one on the r5 tape' b'vtwm: vtwm offers some of the virtual-desktop features of swm, with a' b'single-root window implementation; it is based on the r4 twm and is available' b'on archive servers. a new version, vtwm-5.0, is based on r5.9 and is available' b'from export. b"tvtwm: tom's virtual tab window manager is also based on the r4 twm" b'and provides a virtual desktop modeled on the virtual-root window of swm. it is' b'available on archive servers' b"olvwm: the vtwm-style virtual-desktop added to sun's olwm. it is" b'available on archive servers; version is on export.' b"mvwm: the vtwm-style virtual-desktop added to osf's mwm. a beta version" b'source license to osf/motif b'ncdwm: the window manager local to ncd terminals offers an mwm look' b"xdswm: the window manager local to visual technology's terminals" b'twm offers virtual screens in the fashion of hp vuewm; source is on export.' b'version also offers the window overview used in vtwm and tvtwm.' b"vuewm: hp's mwm-based window manager offers configurable workspaces." b"4dwm: sgi's enhanced mwm" b'piewm: this version of tvtwm offers pie menus' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"it needn't. what is probably happening is that you are running your" b'window manager as the last job in your .xsession or .xinitrc file; your x' b'session runs only as long as the last job is running, and so killing your' b'window manager is equivalent to logging out. instead, run the window manager in' b'the background, and as the last job instead invoke something safe like:' b'exec xterm -name login -rv -iconic' b'or any special client of your devising which exits on some user action.' b'your x session will continue until you explicitly logout of this window,' b'whether or not you kill or restart your window manager.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'although no known window manager directly supports such a feature b'which may be equivalent to writing out a .xinitrc or .xsession file naming the' b'geometry and wm_command of each application (but olvwm may have something' b'close) there is a contributed application which does much of what you are' b'looking for, although it is not as complete as the sunview program toolplaces.' b'look for the application "xplaces" on an archive-server near you. there are' b'several versions of this program floating around; look for a recent vintage.' b'[10/90]' b"some new pseudo session-managers such as hp's vuewm provide for the" b'saving of sessions including information on the geometry of currently-running' b'applications and the resource database.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"dec's session manager will start dxwm up by default. to override this," b'add to your .xdefaults file something like this line, naming the full pathname:' b'sm.windowmanagername: /wherever/usr/bin/x11/your_favorite_wm' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'you can turn auto-repeat on or off by using "xset r on|off". the x' b"protocol, however, doesn't provide for varying the auto-repeat rate, which is" b'a capability not supported by all systems.' b'some servers running on systems that support this, however, may provide' b'command-line flags to set the rate at start-up time. if you have control over' b'server start-up (see the man pages for xinit and xdm), you can invoke the' b'server with the chosen settings; for example, you can start the xsun server' b'from mit with the options "-ar1 -ar2 to reduce the sensitivity of the' b'keyboard.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'there is no method of arranging for a particular string to be' b'produced when you press a particular key. the xmodmap client, which is useful' b'for moving your ctrl and esc keys to useful places, just rearranges keys and' b'does not do "macro expansion."' b'some (few) clients, including xterm and several x-based editors,' b'accept a translation resource such as:' b'xterm*vt100.translations: #override b'<keyf1: string("setenv display unix:0")' b'which permits the shorthand f1 to be pressed to reset the display locally' b'within an xterm; it takes effect for new xterm clients. to include control' b'characters in the string, use \\nnn, where nnn is the octal encoding of the' b'control character you want to include.' b'window managers, which could provide this facility, do not yet; nor' b'has a special "remapper" client been made available.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'' b'"just the faqs, ma\'am." joe 